cripts/`\n- It **does not have** `src/`, `package.json`, etc. (so there’s nothing here to edit to add KM support)\n\nSo the place we can actually change code is almost certainly still:\n\n- `tmp-wtd-package-engine-repo` (this one *does* have `src/`, `server.js`, adapters, etc.)\n\n### Important (security)\nWhen you pasted/printed that `.env`, it exposed live secrets (passwords + API keys). Assume they’re compromised now.\nYou should **rotate**:\n- WheelPros password/token\n- Wheel-Size API key\n- Google Places API key  \n…and replace them in Vercel/wherever they’re stored. (Also make sure `.env` is not committed anywhere.)\n\n### Back to the KM key in Vercel\nEven if “the KM API key is set in Vercel”, `tmp-wtd-package-engine-repo` currently has **zero** KM env vars and **no KM adapter**. It only supports:\n- WheelPros (wheels)\n- Wheel-Size (fitment)\n- TireConnect scraping (optional, via widget/location)\n\nSo the KM key in Vercel is likely being used by a *different service* (maybe the Next.js site repo), not this package engine.\n\n### Next step: tell me which deployment is calling KM\nTwo quick questions:\n\n1) What is the URL of the backend your storefront calls for tires?  \n   (Example: `https://<something>.vercel.app/api/tires` or a Railway URL, etc.)\n\n2) Is that backend deployed from `tmp-wtd-package-engine-repo`, or from a different repo (maybe `warehouse-tire-site`)?\n\nIf you point me at the repo that contains the Vercel deployment for the storefront API, I’ll find the KM env var name it expects and the exact code path where results are getting collapsed to 1.","textSignature":"msg_08e128b880ff85f90069baa8142edc819ab53152c327c633a3"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openai","model":"gpt-5.2","usage":{"input":28464,"output":555,"cacheRead":114944,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":143963,"cost":{"input":0.049812,"output":0.00777,"cacheRead":0.0201152,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0776972}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773840401206}}
